== Arena Rules ==


The Southport Arena welcomes you!


This building's interior is warded to facilitate duels and close-quarters war games. The rules are as follows:

1. Do not try to circumvent the wardings in any attempt to permanently harm, mutilate, or kill your opponent. You will be barred from future entry into the Arena (and possibly Southport) if you do.

2. The laws of Southport and the Kingdom of Cetha remain in effect here, except for the spellcasting laws. You may cast spells, summon creatures, and transform yourself in any way that you please, provided you remain inside the building. Leaving the arena into Southport will reinstate these waived laws.

3. If you are normally banned from Southport due to the banishment list, you may still participate in the Arena. If you leave into Southport proper, you will be killed on sight.

TAKE FROM WITHIN.

JUST KIDDING. I'M LOCKED.
This wide belt is made of thick leather and studded with iron. It grants the wearer the strength of a giant and the ability to make devastating melee attacks.

Iron plated greaves forged for the most determined of dwarven warriors with the Dark Spire. Their warriors would wear these heavily enchanted pieces of armor, and become near unbeatable. Unfortunately, all but a small few of these were lost when the giants of fire and ice overtook the mountain.

Regardless of the defeat of the dwarves long ago, these boots still retain their durability and ability to retain a blow, just as their previous owners.

It’s a well known fact that elves are foppish gits, barely able to lift their own swords without a limp-wristed floppy motion. It was for this very reason that these boots were forged. 

The master elven smith Yal’driirmathileh Mastiiramaeviil, spent many long hours making these boots for the elven protectors of the long forgotten court of Myth Drannor. When the kingdom fell, many of these boots wwere lost, some fell into the hands of those responsible for the fall, others are a prized possession from a dragons hoard. 

Perhaps the adventurer who has stumbled upon them now will use them to serve their intended purpose. Perhaps though, they have simply made another step along the road to obscurity.

This magnificent book bears the symbol of Mystra upon both the front and reverse cover. The true power of this book is merely awaiting to be awakened.


Long ago, a group of Mystra's chosen clerics set forth upon a task. A task to create an item that would allow them to forever store and harness their collective power over the arcane, with the divine leadership of the Lady of Magic. In time, this book was bestowed upon each cleric... Some say it was a working of their own hands, others, a gift from the lady herself...

No matter its origin, this tome now bears an endless array of pages, their arcane presence forever used to help control the weave and to ensure it never falls to The Shadow Weave.
The symbol of Mystra rests upon the cover of this elegant book.

Long ago there was a halfling marauder known as Merino Lightpalm, a sneaky little hin much like most the other little buggers. He stole from the rich and, well, kept it all for himself.

His name spread across the land of some distant town that so very few care about - might've been Daggerford, who knows - and his name caught the gaze of a certain young magician. A diviner by nature, this young wizard thought he could create such a tool to ensure that this sneaky hin couldn't steal from him.

The fact that this wizard no longer possesses the item in your hand is proof enough of how that worked out.

This item, among all the rest of the wizard's prized treasures, was taken and duplicated for profit... 


The item itself is a small opal held from a silver chain that fits around one's head, above the ears, much as a crown would. The gemstone rests suspended across the wearer's forehead, and through this the wearer can gain a potent arcane view of their surroundings through a mere act of focusing on the item.

How did the mage get this stolen from him again...?

When you peer into this smooth orb, all you can see is gray mist. Once you turn to look elsewhere, you catch a glimpse of a white skull in purple smoke, or possibly the figure of a mask, in the corner of your eye. Other times, you could swear something glitters inside the orb. If you look again, however, there’s nothing there.

The common adventurer is completely oblivious to the origin of these orbs, and they’re a mystery even to the greatest sages. They're often said to be crafted by thieves' guilds in the south, or to be sacred items belonging to the clergy of Cyric. Some have even heard rumours claiming them to be the trapped fragments of an ancient god, and the one who gathers them together ascends to divinity.

The most determined seekers might come across a few scholars' claims suggesting the involvement of the Guardian of Liars. Should anyone ask the remaining worshippers of Leira, however, they’d hear the same old stories about dead gods, Mask's thieves, and a few new ones. Whatever the truth, the orb you hold now is clearly a potent magical item, especially for those who want to learn a secret or two - and twist them some before passing on the information, perhaps.
This belt assists the adventurer by providing proper posture. Perfect for those who want to stay on the road for lengthy periods it increases ones endurance and longevity.
Whether the wearer wants to remain hidden or feels the need to inspire awe as a displacer beast, the cloak of hidden things provides a boon to many adventurers of various skill.
These boots are perfectly suited to wizards who subject themselves to the counter forces of their craft on a daily basis.
Ancient gloves of this design where created by the Imaskari Artificers to aid and in their creations.

An eyecatching pair of boots, loving handcrafted and stitched with super precision. Offering the finest qualities in both protection and fashion, for the adventurer whose main concern is looking good.

Cloaks of Sanctuary offer the wearer the benefits of the spells, Greater Sanctuary, Improved Invisibility and Invisibility. Rumour has it they were created from the skins of Fey. 

More than likely though some enterprising wizard found an expedient method of mass producing these cloaks.
This unassuming scarab is divested of amazing powers of recuperation. Heiroglyphs adorn the piece. Apparently blessed with abundant powers of protection.

Common place bands of metal are worn on the fingers as ornamentation. This ring however is not commonplace.

Providing protection from blows and increased ability to deflect incoming attacks rings of protection and prevention are among the most sought after items.
Crafted from the scale of a blue dragon and welded together with the bile sack of a juvenile green, armors of this quality are sought after for the potent protection they afford.
The scale of a white and a red dragon have been magnificently laminated together to create a plate mail of near unparalleled protection against the polar opposites of fire and ice.

These hoods were designed to promote Archery amongst human kind, to put them on an equal footing with their Elven counterparts.

Obviously since adventurers find them as loot, such footing was never reached.

Ioun stones are well known to possess different powers depending upon their color.  When activated they orbit around the head of their owner.  Only one ioun stone may be activated at a time. The purple ioun stone adds two points of regeneration while active.
This flawless gem radiates strong magic and seems to glow from within. The exact nature of the gem's enchantment remains a mystery.

All seemed lost the dark day that the island Zanshibon was absorbed into the abyss. Many lamented the great evil that had happened. One however who had once called the island home and had been selling his wares when it was lost found new focus and drive as a craftsman. They say he forged many shields and sets of armor so the agents of the abyss could be made to pay. His last shield made days before his death, his last defence is potent piece of protection indeed.

A pair of worn leather boots, with the brown polish faded from use. By all accounts, they should be about ready to fall apart, but as the handful of wearers have found out, they simply do not damage in any way. No manner what treacherous roads they walk, through bogs, woods or deserts, they remain in the same state as they were before. In fact, the more canny of wearers have noticed that in terms of desperation, these boots direct toward the safer of paths, allowing their wearer to avoid deadly pitfalls and traps. 

While nothing has been confirmed, the more vocal of dwarven kind have proclaimed them to be a gift from the deity Marthammor Duin, though others are less enthusiastic at the fervor these dwarves have shown trying to claim the boots for themselves.

Both heavy and beautiful in equal measures, these bracers are lined with rich gemstones of the ruby, emerald and diamond varieties. They passed hands a number of times among noble-folk, being treated as little more than a way of demonstrating one's wealth, as only the upper echelons of society were able to afford such an expensive pair of bracers. However, after one such noble found himself using them to fend off a gang of bandits, it became quickly apparent that these were no mere decorations - they fend off even the most enchanted of weapons with nary a scratch. Despite many attempts, their design simply hasn't been replicated, though some mages have claimed that the gemstones are cut in a manner more suited to a gemstone golem than a piece of jewelry.

Also known as the healing hands of Salandra or The First Duty, gloves such as these are said to have been created and used by the very first of Salandra's faithful after her martyrdom and ascension to divinity. They have only recently begun to resurface and while the truth of this origin is a matter of some debate, given how potent the gloves are and how they can seemingly bestow the most inept with the touch of a trained healer one might wonder if there isn't something to the legend after all.

These pale yellow gloves look to be mostly mundane other than the subtle embroidery of a single daffodil on the palm, and it was this reason that they became so infamous among a cabal of dubious merchants that roamed Baldur's Gate. Tired of barely scraping enough profit to get by, they were responsible for a price hike across the region that was said to be directly combated by gloves of this make - supposedly, just handling items while wearing these gloves was enough to pinpoint the exact value of it, down to the last copper coin. 

While a maker never came forth directly, the temple of Waukeen kept an especially close eye upon those merchants, and many agree they were responsible for putting them back on the straight and narrow.

Celestial, abyssal and infernal runes line each digit of these jet black gloves, and it doesn't take long to reveal that these are no mere decorations - performing certain hand gestures will light up each rune of a certain language in turn, and when all runes of the same language are glowing brightly, a creature of the matching kind will be pulled from its home to do the wearer's bidding. While they've since lost their name, they were a common sight on a Red Wizard who had a flair for the dramatic, regularly summoning servants to assist in studies via complicated, impressive displays of the theatrical. It was said each rune had a small enchantment to store memories, and with the sheer amount of runes on these gloves, they promise to impart a large collection of knowledge upon any who wears them.

The Crouching Lemur monastery is situated near Guldorand and is said to be the home of a powerful, legendary monk. Many have joined the monastary for a chance to meet and perhaps be trained by the master. It is said that incredibly powerful gloves were once produced by the master himself, using a secret method, to reward those who had been under his teaching and had shown the most potential. They were designed to have small sharp blades come around the knuckles area when making a fist, and were said to have chains with specially coated lemur hair at their ends that could severely harm their victim's eyes if they were swung right.

The master however regretted crafting these when he noticed several of his old pupils grew so much confidence in themselves after receiving their gift (knowing who had made the gloves and how they were made) that it influenced their young minds enough that they thought themselves invincible. It is unclear what have become of the pupils or of those gloves, but what you have here ressembles what is described in the stories. If they were the gloves of legend, this would be quite the rare find as gloves of that qualiber have not been since re-made and their fabrication method has been kept a secret by the old legendary monk who first created them.

Previously commonly found worn by the patrons of the old Sanctuary of Sin, and named thereafter, these gloves help their wearers slip past defenses and set ambushes for their foes. It is likely why they were rather popular in the days of the Sanctuary, when even getting down to the bar required navigating a myriad of traps and dangers, and dead patrons were a daily occurance.

In some circles of nature, a somber tradition prevails. At the passing of an agent, when their time has ultimately come, it is not uncommon that their animal companion should die with them out of supposed grief. To this end, many workers of the natural world have seen fit to burn both master and beast upon the funeral pyre, together.

From their ashes, a Great Druid then crafts a charm to be passed on to others within the circle. The bond between the two survives even in death, and their kinship empowers those who have followed in their footsteps.

Legend tells of an unnamed Justicar of Kohlingen who, upon realizing a grave threat against the City of Paladins, sent a dozen of his most capable Defenders to face it. The tale again falls into murkiness, but its resolution in all retellings is bittersweet. While the foe was bested, all crusaders were lost to to their injuries. The most stalwart of the city's protectors, these twelve peers were commemorated in a ceremony that created one ring in memory of each. For a few decades, it became tradition that new rings would be forged at the passing of a Kohlingen Defender, though the practice fell out of use some time before the group's second Founding. Even so, these rings can still be found in the far and treacherous reaches that brave templar once journeyed.

The tales of these rings inevitably lead back to the Shadow Plane, though there the trail runs cold. Most local explanations will center around Shadowscape, one of exceedingly few hospitable places in the realm.

Some have held that Grandmistress Luriko of the Three Steps Academy distributes them to students who show promise. Many have suggested they were crafted at the request of the Shadowbornes, thereby being Sharran in nature. Others still allude to strange and clandestine Shadow Magic, set apart from the dire connotations of the Dark Twin's web.

Twinkling like starlight, the jeweled bauble keeps its secrets, much like those who would wear it.

Many years ago, the Heartwood Grove in place where the Oakmist Vale Grove now resides. A limited amount of these rings were made for the trusted members to protect both the land and Balance, providing them the insight to act as protectors. The rings were thought lost or destroyed when the grove became corrupted, leaving the forests infested with undead and otherworldly creatures.

These rings have recently shown up in the strangest of places, seemingly of their own accord. With the corruption now in the distant past, perhaps they have deemed it a worthy time to aid with the protection of the Balance once more.

It is written:

"Nabessa the Sword Saint sat in the presence of his men in camp, repairing his mail. To the ferrier he called: "Bring me the weakest of your links that I might mend my armor." The blacksmith protested, fearing embarrassment in being judged by the worst of his work. He asked: "Sire, could not I bring you the finest of my links, that you can be sure that your mail shall hold?"

Nabessa plucked a nail from the post of a tent and bent it around his thumb. He looped it between two lengths of chain and held it up for all to see. As he pulled the lengths apart, he spoke: "A chain be only as strong as its weakest link. As a ring is to mail, so too is a man to an army. If the least of them might hold, it is assured that all shall hold." The Saint then gathered more nails and bent them as rings for his men in camp, where merry was made until the morn."

-Squire Omos of Kohlingen, Year Unknown

Much of the north was once the domain of giants and trolls. It is said when the first men came to the Ostland, Cariagh and Wiltun regions that all was ruled by Grundisvarg the witch queen of trolls. Each of the locals islands claims one of its heroes slew her and while none can prove who did so powerful rune carved troll bone rings are often found that claim were crafted from the troll queen's bones.

Simple and smooth, this timepiece ticks along. Consisting only of a numbered metal loop and a series of crossing beams, one's mind boggles at how it might operate.

There is something familiar in this curious timepiece. You have seen it before. Or maybe it comes from a time yet to arrive. In the twinkling of a eye, one might see it in the reflecting metal. A huge figure in purple and gold armor, hourglasses and clocks embedded therein. And behind it, looming, a many-legged creature of shadow, not of this world or any other.

Perhaps time will tell. Perhaps time has already told.

In the Year of the Shield, the area once known as Stonehold was conquered by the Emberblaze family alongside the Dark Flight, a fell cabal of chromatic dragons. This newly renamed settlement of Wyrmhold would fight a fierce battle with Benwick, ultimately destroying it before being destroyed itself.

It is not known when these idols were made, nor whose remains they now hold. The spirit of that time, however, when dragons waged war over the Amian Isle, continues to rage on through its power. It will bestow the gift of purging fire to any weapon that would claim it.

An eye of a Yowler, an undead Displacer Beast. Rogues and other adventurers often wear the eyes as good luck charms, believing them to aid in non-detection as well as inheriting the Yowler's ability to ward off negative energy.

These beasts once upon a time roamed the Forest of Despair, but were butchered by the Malarites when the servants of the Beastlord were chased out of Amia Forest and were in need of a new home.

Some weapons were forged by heroes on noble quests. This axe not so much. It was a cold winter night in the drinking halls of the dwarf folk. Much was the drinking and boasting when the king proclaimed any dwarf that could slay a frost giant jarl and all of his huskarls single-handedly while drunk would have a weapon fit for a king made for them. The first and only dwarf to speak was Khulrak Redaxe, a battlerager who was said the now-famous phrase "hold my tankard and watch this".

The drunken dwarven nobles followed Khulrak to a well known frost giant encampment and watched from a distance as the mad dwarf charged into battle. The fight was bloody and frenzied and when dawn broke all the giants lay dead, as did Khulrak, though the battle rager died with a grin.

A dwarf of his word, the king had his smiths forge this axe from Khulrak's spiked helmet. It is said that it gave the axe the power to strike with a drunken frenzied battlerager's headbutt.

Old warriors tell tales of two blades, one of cleansing song, the other of corrupting darkness. The two bastard swords found themselves in the possession of many a hero and villain, but over countless wars, numerous assassinations, and endless violence, they became lost along with the names of those who wielded them.

In the west of Amia, there once stood a gauntlet of eternal war waged between Celestials and Demons. In the final battle, it was said the blades Purity and Filth both reappeared for a short while. However, in the blinding flash that took the Bastion from this plane, they were gone yet again. Rising Sun cultists, worshipers of both heaven and hell, now claim the land as their own. They speak in dark whispers of what became of the legendary weapons:

"In vice, there is virtue. In damnation, there is rapture. And even in the most wretched filth, there is a purity which begs to be reclaimed."

Carrying the insignia of a now disbanded criminal organization previously based out of South Cordor, this dagger seems to have been designed specifically to locate and punch trough elemental weak spots on their target. Given their targets were often seasoned adventurers, this was usually a necessity as many often carry gear giving them resistances of one type or another.

Wyrmfall is a yearly commemorative festival held in Kohlingen to celebrate brave accomplishments against the prophesised Dark Flight of Tiamat. During the annual Kohlingen Wyrmfall Celebration of 1383, festivities experienced interruptions from beastmen raiders under command of the late beastman king Grushnagth, the Red Claw. Pilfered from the rightful hands of a righteous Silver Dragon Knight, now the sword is a perversion mired with vile toxins brewed in the putrid beastman pits.

The black dragon Myrk was among the dark flight that terrorized Amia. Wicked and vile, she was the epitome of her kind and terrorised the swamp lands. It was said one day she came upon a lone bard and jokingly said if he could make her shed a tear he could pass with his life. The bard agreed and whispered to her a poem that is said to have been so soul crushing it can never be spoke out loud. A single tear fell from the dragon's eye, landing upon the bard's sword - he named it Myrk's Lament mere moments before the treacherous black dragon killed him for making her sad.

After Myrk's death it is said the sword and others near it in her lair absorbed some of the acid, magic and fear inherent to the great black dragon.

"Black and White, Dark and Light, see me not, within your sight."

Extremely rare, master smiths of far away notions copied the design from weapons taken from fallen Kara-Turan soldiers. The unusual weapons were carried by high ranking court assassins, and those that knew the meaning of the blade, and saw it drawn, usually did not live long enough to tell about it. Imbued with both forces of life, there is a balance to the blade that slips in, unnoticed, until it is too late.

The cry of the banshee is a nightmare to most. However, to at least one bardic palemaster from Tarkuul it was beauty. He laboured day and night trying to mimic that dreadful keening but every sword was a failure. They could scream, they could howl but none were perfect. Driven mad by his own failure, he cast the wailing swords to the sea and fell into a deep and profound melancholy that lingers to this day.

The sneaky little tricksters and thieves of Brandobaris that have resided in Bendir Dale call themselves Harlequins, and love to laugh - usually at the expense of others, because who wants to pay for embarrassment, when so many are just getting in line for it, and it is not their fault most 'tallers' don't get the sometimes harmless little pranks they find themselves blindly walking into. A sword like this is long enough to keep them at bay, if one has to resort to such measures, and possibly get in a really good sneaky strike, especially since one of the many mages of the Dale have given it a little bit of magical energy to get in that last laugh, and the blade is equal in sharpness to a true Harlequin's wit.

Before the Underkingdom, also known as "the Spires", fell to the duergar and then to the giants, the once powerful Dwarven Kingdom was known as Dornat Murr.

Among many famous weapons and armors, the dwarven guards wielded doule-sided warhammers. One side flat and able to smash their foe, but a pick on the other side to pierce through even the most sturdy of armors. Feared were those hammers who could wreak doom onto the dwarven foes.

Lucky souls can still rarely find one of those masterpieces of dwarven craftsmenship, scattered all over the isles.

Once there was a haunted manor near the holy city of Amia. Many were the tales of its evils and undead haunts. One such tale is of a young fighter who lost her party to a horde of ghouls and soon found herself disarmed. Desperate for a weapon, she ripped a massive gothic door knocker off a door and used it as a brutal blunt weapon. With the ghouls slain, she decided to bless the door knocker and craft others like it.

Urzgloth Ullthok was a half-orc female raised in the brutal tribe of Many Arrows. Little more than a slave, she escaped only to become lost in the spine of the world. Starving and freezing to death she found the legendary Black Raven Monastery. There she was taught how to find peace of mind and given the name of Iron Tigress. Developing a more aggressive variant of the Black Raven style she crafted a set of fighting claws in honor of her new name. While she owned many such claws, only the best still carry her name.

As with many exquisitely-crafted bows, many attribute these to the elves, especially as the first examples of their kind started to appear in the hands in the upper ranks of Winyan soldiers. Yet, the few elven scholars fortunate enough to closely examine these bows argue that they have no origin of elvenkind at all - rather than to precisely pierce their target, these weapons are built for a more brutal purpose. Instead of focusing on aim and precision, these bows focus on speed, fast enough that the wind currents left in the wake of arrows fired are a danger in themselves, ripping at the target in a vicious manner akin to a flying saw. Such violent methods are rarely found in elven crafts, leaving the origins of these weapons much a mystery.

A prototype of the "Ring of Improved Evasion" this ring enhances the wearer's ability to evade harm as if they had the evasion ability.
